UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85133657030&doi=10.1093%2Fjscr%2Frjac281&partnerID=40&md5=1529599e0ebc8f2394858d2318e1b748
AB  - Lead exposure in India is common in industries that may present with nonspecific signs and symptoms or symptoms of toxicity, depending on the amount of lead absorbed. We are presenting two case reports of occupational lead exposure in a lead-based battery manufacturing unit, which were presented as intestinal obstruction. Both the patients aged 28 and 24-year old presented with complaints of pain in the abdomen with blood lead levels of 61.1 and 85 μg/dl, respectively. The diagnosis was made clinically before any other radiological investigation or intervention. Both the patients were treated conservatively with D-Penicillamine, following which, both the patients improved symptomatically and the blood lead level also decreased. The importance of a detailed history of occupation & clinically diagnosing such patient will avoid unnecessary investigation and intervention. This will help to reach the correct diagnosis in such cases.  © 2022 Published by Oxford University Press and JSCR Publishing Ltd.
